The foreign exchange market in South Africa is larger than ever, with new traders emerging daily as they try their hand at speculating on the price movements of major, minor, and exotic currencies in the largest, most liquid market amongst several other major markets in the world. The forex market has seen rollercoaster highs and lows in the past two years with the emergence and spread of Covid-19 around the world. In addition, the impacts that followed were also driving factors in an already volatile market space, where retail traders kept their hands firmly on safe-haven assets to diversify their portfolios and keep their capital safe. For 2022 analysts predict that the forex market is set to be driven by two major factors, namely inflation and (as no surprise), Covid-19. These factors are set to drive the monetary policy decisions of central banks around the world. This relates to the fact that the forex market is consistently evaluating inflation data to provide clues of when central banks are set to raise or cut interest rates. This is attributable to the fact that high interest will boost a currency while lower interest rates will cause a currency to depreciate. South Africa has one of the best and most reputable market regulators that oversees all forex trading, the Financial Sector Conduct Authority (FSCA). The FSCA is busy rolling out a new license, the Over-The-Counter (OTC) License for Derivative Providers With this new regulatory framework, the FSCA can reduce the risk that retail and institutional forex traders in South Africa face, effectively creating a safe environment for market participants, subsequently ensuring that South Africa is aligned with the G20 requirements in terms of OTC derivatives market regulation. South Africa has a bustling forex trading scene and traders must remember that while countless forex brokers offer traders the sun, moon, and stars, trading with a trusted and well-regulated forex broker can make or break a traderâ€™s trad